pullRequest.body:
This adds `!‚Çë[1, 2, 3]` notation for `(WithLp.equiv 2 (‚àÄ _ : Fin 3, _)).symm ![1, 2, 3]`, which is a term of type `EuclideanSpace ùïú (Fin 3)`.

This reduces the temptation to write the type-incorrect `![1, 2, 3]` that has the wrong norm.

[Notation Zulip poll](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/287929-mathlib4/topic/Notation.20for.20vectors.20in.20euclidean.20space/near/476796192).

We could consider introducing this more generally for other Lp-norms; notation suggestions welcome. This might be an argument for using `!‚ÇÇ[1, 2, 3]` instead of `!‚Çë[1, 2, 3]`

@digama0, any idea what's up with `uncaught exception: parser 'subscript' was not found` in the CI logs for `lake exe check-yaml`?

My guess is that one of the linters is elaborating something in an empty environment, and it's failing to interpret the syntax objects. See [`6ed0fa63`](https://github.com/leanprover-community/batteries/commit/6ed0fa636779101a5619955b804d4786445d7e38) which was about a similar issue.

Here there's no panic to speak of, and the issue seems to be just a regular IO exception being thrown.

I don't think linters are to blame, since adding
```lean
Lean.Elab.Command.lintersRef.set #[]
```
to the start of `main` doesn't help.

@digama0, I think these lines are somehow not running:

https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/85ec5bfdc334783e7cc63ce1f1a3679eaacba054/Mathlib/Util/Superscript.lean#L279-L285

source.title: Add missing informal + Lean statements for four missing problems

nodes.body: @digama0, any idea what's up with `uncaught exception: parser 'subscript' was not found` in the CI logs for `lake exe check-yaml`?

My guess is that one of the linters is elaborating something in an empty environment, and it's failing to interpret the syntax objects. See [`6ed0fa63`](https://github.com/leanprover-community/batteries/commit/6ed0fa636779101a5619955b804d4786445d7e38) which was about a similar issue.

Here there's no panic to speak of, and the issue seems to be just a regular IO exception being thrown.

I don't think linters are to blame, since adding
```lean
Lean.Elab.Command.lintersRef.set #[]
```
to the start of `main` doesn't help.

@digama0, I think these lines are somehow not running:

https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/85ec5bfdc334783e7cc63ce1f1a3679eaacba054/Mathlib/Util/Superscript.lean#L279-L285
